
 ******* Example 02 ******* 

 January 30, 2026
 New York University, New York
 Avalos Research Group
          &
 University of Nevada, Reno
 Varganov Research Group

 This example tests calculation of Marcus-Levich-Jortner rate constant with FGR program.

 Inspired by the work of Gorgon, S.; Lv, K.; Grüne, J.; Drummond1, B. H.; Myers, W. K.; Londi, G.;
 Ricci, G.; Valverde, D.; Tonnelé, C.; Murto, P.; Romanov, A. S.; Casanova, D.; Dyakonov, V.; 
 Sperlich, A.; Beljonne, D.; Olivier, Y.; Li, F.; Friend, R. H.; Evans, E. W. 
 Reversible spin-optical interface in  luminescent organic radicals. Nature 2023, 620, 538-544. 
 Fast D1 to D2 reverse internal conversion in the tris(2,4,6-trichlorophenyl) methyl-carbazole-anthracene 
 (TTM-1Cz-An) luminescent neutral radical in toluene solution. 

 Geometry and Hessian of the D2 state were calculated with TD-DFT using the Tamn-Dancoff approximation 
 at the CAM-B3LYP/def2-SVP//CPCM(Toluene) level of theory. The geometry of the D1 state was approximated with
 the geometry of nearly isoenergetic first excited Q1 state at the CAM-B3LYP/def2-SVP//CPCM(Toluene) level of DFT. 
 Electronic coupling constant was adopted from the work above. All calculations were done with the ORCA 6.1 electronic structure package.  

 For more information, see the paper above and, hopefully, our second release paper coming soon.

	>>>>>  Predicted results (from work above) at 298 K <<<<<

      D1 to D2 RIC rate constant: k = 6.6 x 10^9 s-1.

       >>>>> FGR results at T = 300 K <<<<<

       >>>>>  Canonical MLJ rate constant  <<<<<

          MLJ formula: k = 2.7 x 10^9 s-1.

